The bill aims to revoke parts of the UK government's 2016 Trade Union Act. It would mean current restrictions on industrial action in the NHS, the fire service and the police would be removed, and it would make changes to the public sector unions' pay-related rights. It replaces the 2012 Trade Union Amendment Bill.

The proposed changes include:

 The government will be able to hire temporary, fixed-term, and contract staff without union consent, in circumstances that are not currently permissible (i.e. the government would need to get prior consent in certain circumstances to hire fixed-term, short-term or contract staff);
 All existing arrangements allowing industrial action over pay claims would be abolished for fixed-term, short-term and temporary staff;
 All existing arrangements allowing industrial action over pay claims would be abolished for public sector temporary staff, who would have to give 12-week notice to their employer before a decision took effect;
 The government would be able to reduce annual pay settlements
